<paragraph id="8BB73696C626FFED0D83DBC1FCE7FC8D" blockId="110.[151,1436,222,831]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C626FFED0D83DBC1FE91FD47" bold="true" box="[199,273,732,757]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Notes.</emphasis>
The white spot on CuA 
<subScript id="178C34D3C626FFED0F6CDBF6FDB0FD4B" attach="left" box="[552,560,747,761]" fontSize="6" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">1</subScript>
and apparently fused abdominal tergites indicate that this species belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D15C626FFED0DD3DA1EFEB3FCA9" authorityName="KITS &amp; MARSHALL" authorityYear="2013" box="[151,307,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilantrops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C626FFED0DD3DA1EFEB3FCA9" box="[151,307,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Poecilantrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It appears quite similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D15C626FFED0F31DA19FC8CFCA9" authorityName="KITS &amp; MARSHALL" authorityYear="2013" box="[629,780,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilantrops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plaumanni">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C626FFED0F31DA19FC8CFCA9" box="[629,780,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">P. plaumanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for the fused tergites and the head and tarsomere colour. It is not described pending discovery of male specimens.
</paragraph>
